Hi Thomas,

In 3.4 the flow-route protocol statement (flow component) is treated as a list. While the standard allows all kinds of ranges exactly like it does for port numbers.

This is not really a bug - we just noticed that it is impossible to have a configuration like below to announce a route with protocol matching like it works with ports (ranges of protocols):

For example:

         route {
           match {
                source 10.12.255.0/24;
                destination 10.11.255.0/24;
                source-port =3 =4 >200&<210;
                protocol =3 =4 >200&<210;
           }
           then {
             accept;
           }

in the configuration/ancient.py we hacked this in order to have the protocol be treated like ports... (with all the drawbacks): 

        def _flow_route_protocol (self, scope, tokens):
                return self._flow_generic_condition(scope,tokens,FlowIPProtocol)

however this may break named-protocol configurations like this (we did not test):

             protocols =tcp =udp >tcp&<udp

Many of the other flow components are also treated as a list which may be perfectly fine for most applications. But may not allow to use the full flexibility of the RFC itself.

Cheers

Christoph

Hi folks, 

I have an extension that should run only after the kernel is ready.  I am doing something like below:

```
define(['base/js/namespace'], function(Jupyter) {
    var ajaxCall = $.get('/some/url');
    function load_ipython_extension() {
        Jupyter.notebook.events.on('kernel_ready.Kernel', function() { 
             ajaxCall.done(myCustomFunction);
        });
    }
});
```

Questions:  

1. Can I  assume that the load_ipython_extension function of this extension will run before the ``kernel_ready.Kernel`` event is fired ?  Otherwise my extension never initializes (``myCustomFunction`` is not called)
1. Is this the best way to write an extension ? Is there a ``kernel.isReady()`` function that I can alternatively use in case the extension didn't get a chance to register before the event was fired ?

I looked into code and found that extensions are loaded [here](https://github.com/jupyter/notebook/blob/e1ba0075f6c5d901f67918e41f434b1788d592f8/notebook/static/notebook/js/main.js#L211), but we are not waiting on them.  The notebook is [loaded soon after](https://github.com/jupyter/notebook/blob/e1ba0075f6c5d901f67918e41f434b1788d592f8/notebook/static/notebook/js/main.js#L232) which in turn fires kernel events.

